<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="512" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d512">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/1058</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <dateline>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-02">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 2, 1914</hi>.</date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11:45 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                            <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                            <p>964. Your 433, October 31. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward
                                    Grey</persName> promises to give me such a report as you ask on
                                the ship <hi rend="italic">Kroonland</hi> at earliest moment
                                possible. Its detention is not a seizure.</p>
                            <p>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward</persName> informs me that
                                his Government found evidence that the copper on the Italian
                                steamers <persName corresp="#p_SGMAD1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">San Giovanni</hi>
                                </persName> and <hi rend="italic">Regina d’Italia</hi> was destined
                                for belligerent territory. This Government therefore prohibits its
                                delivery and will itself buy it and pay for it. The delay of the
                                steamers was caused by the fact that the Copper was at the bottom of
                                the ships. They have been allowed to proceed under guarantee that
                                the copper will be delivered to British authorities on return
                                voyage.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>